{{recipesummary||6-8 persons||3}}
{{recipe}} | [[Cookbook:Cuisine of the United States|United States]]
'''Succotash''' - A recipe with a great name.
==Ingredients== *2 quarts shelled [[Cookbook:Lima Bean|lima beans]] *24 ears of [[Cookbook:Maize|corn]] cut off the cob *1 pound of pickled [[Cookbook:Pork|pork]] (typically omitted) *2 tablespoons [[Cookbook:Baking sugar|sugar]] (can be omitted) *2 tablespoons [[Cookbook:Butter|butter]] (can be omitted or olive oil substituted) *[[Cookbook:Pepper|pepper]]
==Procedure== If using pork, cover pork with water, and parboil it; add beans; then add corn, sugar, butter, and pepper to taste. After corn is added, watch carefully to keep from scorching. Serve.
==Notes, tips, and variations== A red bell pepper (chopped) can be added.
==References== * Mrs. S. A. Powers, “New England Succotash” in {{Gutenberg|1084|name=Recipes Tried and True}}
{{wikipedia}}
[[Category:Pork recipes|Succotash]] [[Category:Corn recipes|Succotash]] [[Category:Bean recipes|Succotash]] [[Category:Boiled recipes]] [[Category:Side dish recipes]] [[Category:American recipes|Succotash]] [[Category:Native American recipes|Succotash]]

